List of changes I made, probably incomplete, I didn't keep track of them all:
- remove `m_fields->m_pages` and use `m_iconPages` instead
- call `setupCustomPage` inside of `setupPage`
- make `onArrow` high priority, as it reimplements original now
- change `setupPage` priority from BeforePost to BeforePre, as the cursor was broken when swapping icons with Separate Dual Icons
- make `findIconPage` look for the SDI vanilla icon as well, although this technically doesn't change anything, as it only gets called when `setupCustomPage` is about to be called, so this probably doesn't need to be implemented on MI's end, but SDI's; I added it just to be sure, it should probably be removed
- remove `m_fields->m_onSelect` and use `GJGarageLayer::onSelect` directly; some mods, like my own, may completely remove every icon from the pages, so fetching the selector from it becomes impossible
- changed signatures of some methods to receive icon types as arguments instead of using `m_iconType`
- make SDI hooks call `selectTab` (which should re-setup the current page) instead of `setupCustomPage`

issue.title: [Feature] Support The third argument of the lag/lead function supports non-const expr
issue.body:
## Why I'm doing:

Allow column expression (column name, arithmetic, function, etc.) to be used as the default value, aligning StarRocks with PostgreSQL, Oracle, and other major databases.

## What I'm doing:

Fixes #55865

### 2.1 Backend (BE)

| Area                        | Change                                                       |
| --------------------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **`LeadLagState`**          | Adds a `default_value_is_constant` flag.                     |
| **`LeadLagWindowFunction`** | *If* the default expression is a constant, follow the original fast path. *Else* evaluate the expression for each row. Fully supports `IGNORE NULLS` / non-`IGNORE NULLS`, and both lag/lead directions. |
| **Unit Tests**              | New tests `test_lag_without_ignore_nulls` and `test_lag_ignore_nulls` verify constant and column-name defaults. |



### 2.2 Frontend (FE)

| Area           | Change                                                       |
| -------------- | ------------------------------------------------------------ |
| **Analyzer**   | Removes the “default must be constant” restriction and validates general expressions. |
| **Unit Tests** | `AnalyzeFunctionTest#testLeadLagDefaultExpr` and `WindowTest#testLeadLagPlan`. |



### 2.3 Documentation

- Updates **English / Japanese / Chinese** window-function docs with an “Example 3” that uses a column as the default value.

### 2.4 SQL Regression

- Adds a new regression suite `test_lead_lag/` covering forward / backward scans, with and without `IGNORE NULLS`.

pull_request.title: Fix IIS 500.1001 Internal Server Error - Correct deployment structure and entry point
pull_request.body:
This PR resolves the IIS 500.1001 Internal Server Error that was preventing the Node.js application from starting under IISNode hosting.

## Root Cause

The application was failing to start because the root `app.js` entry point was trying to require `./server.js`, but this file didn't exist in the root directory. The actual server file was located at `./apps/pitch/backend/server.js`, causing a module resolution failure that resulted in the opaque IIS 500.1001 error.

## Changes Made

### 1. Fixed Entry Point Path
Updated the root `app.js` to correctly require the backend server:

```javascript
// Before (broken)
const server = require('./server.js');

// After (working)
const server = require('./apps/pitch/backend/server.js');
```

### 2. Established Proper Deployment Structure
- Copied `package.json` from backend to root and installed dependencies
- Copied `web.config` from backend to root for IIS configuration
- Built the client application to create the required `dist` folder

### 3. Verified IISNode Integration
The server properly detects when running under IISNode and exports the Express app instead of starting its own HTTP server:

```javascript
// In server.js
if (process.env.IISNODE_VERSION) {
  module.exports = app;  // Export for IISNode
} else {
  app.listen(PORT);      // Start own server for local dev
}
```

## Testing Results

All critical functionality has been verified:

- ✅ Server loads without startup errors under IISNode environment
- ✅ Express app properly exported with all required methods
- ✅ All critical artifacts found (`generateInstructionRef.js`, `upload.js`, etc.)
- ✅ Routes working: `/simple-test`, `/test`, `/pitch/`, static assets
- ✅ Root redirects correctly to `/pitch`
- ✅ Client application serves and loads assets properly

## Impact

This fix resolves the deployment blocker that was preventing the application from running on IIS/Azure App Service. The application should now start successfully and serve both API endpoints and the React client application.

The changes are minimal and surgical - only correcting the path resolution issue without modifying any business logic or existing functionality.

issue.title: Platform: Add SimpleTextInputExCompatDxe for EFI 1.1 compatibility
issue.body:
This driver provides SimpleTextInputEx protocol support for EFI 1.1 systems that lack native support for this protocol. Specifically designed to enable OpenShell text editor functionality on older UEFI implementations.

Key features:
- EFI 1.1 compatibility layer for SimpleTextInputEx protocol
- Function key support (F1-F11) for OpenShell
- Control character detection and mapping (Ctrl+A through Ctrl+Z)
- Non-intrusive operation with existing text input protocols
- Closes https://github.com/acidanthera/bugtracker/issues/1080

comment.body:
I think going with both is a good idea indeed. I think the right approach to do it should be as follows:

* Create a library (OpenCorePkg/Library/OcTextInputLib) with multiple .inf files with .c code implementing functions necessary to install the SimpleInputEx protocol.
    * OpenCorePkg/Library/OcTextInputLib/OcTextInputLib.inf could offer "normal" variant for use by the drivers.
    * OpenCorePkg/Library/OcTextInputLib/OcTextInputLocalLib.inf could offer "local" variant for use by OpenShell, and will use `OcRegisterBootServicesProtocol` instead of `gBS` within a constructor to install the service.
* In OpenCore we add `OcTextInputLib.inf` dependency and wire things through the configuration.
* In OpenShell we add `OcTextInputLocalLib.inf` dependency and use constructor-based approach to add a protocol.
* Separately we may create an additional driver inside `OpenCorePkg` (or perhaps even some other repository) using `OcTextInputLib.inf`, which can be used to offer compatibility outside of OpenCorePkg (e.g. for firmware injection).

This way we will not need hacks inside `audk`. Let me know if you need help, I guess I could take over after a certain point to perform the integration as I know the project codebase a little better.
